e professional political class, and the national press corps. And every so =
often=E2=80=94the famous face-offs between John F. Kennedy and Richard Nixo=
n in 1960, say, or the solo debate between Ronald Reagan and Jimmy Carter i=
n 1980=E2=80=94they have been known and shown to move the needle appreciabl=
y among voters. But historically speaking, the instances in which debates h=
ave produced tangible electoral effects have been the exception and not the=
 rule.

Bill Clinton didn=E2=80=99t snatch the Oval Office from George H.W. Bush in=
 1992 on the debate stage; 41=E2=80=99s son, George W., didn=E2=80=99t triu=
mph over Al Gore due to the magnum force
of his forensic mastery. The three debates between Barack Obama and John Mc=
Cain in 2008 were all more or less forgotten within days, and Obama=E2=80=
=99s #epicfail against Mitt Romney in the first 2012 debate didn=E2=80=99t =
result in Willard moving into the White House. As a general matter, it=E2=
=80=99s fair to say, presidential debates create a ton of sound and fury, b=
ut portend precious little.

