         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s4_V2">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Many attribute Trum=
p=E2=80=99s ability to pull out a narrow victory against <b>Hillary Clinton=
</b> in 2016 to the final two weeks of the campaign, when he was convinced =
by <b>Steve Bannon </b>and <b>Kellyanne Conway </b>to talk about <i>nothing=
 </i>but the border and China and American manufacturing. There=E2=80=99s b=
een an enduring fantasy that Trump can find his way back to this version of=
 himself; that he will manage to summon that same level of clarity and disc=
ipline and bring it to bear against Harris in the homestretch. <br/><br/>Bu=
t ever since Harris became the de facto nominee, Trump has been verklempt. =
He=E2=80=99s been spinning out and spiraling and unable to maintain a coher=
ent, linear approach to just about anything. I wrote a <u><a href=3D"https:=
//email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSLUk4eHhva=
TJmYTZvSkVpZVVLMD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdHJ1bXBzLXB1bmlzaGlu=
Zy1uZXctc3BsaXQtc2NyZWVuLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHR=
lc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg5JTJGMTUlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZS=
tCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OSUyRjExJTJGMjQlMjlcd=
TAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9c=
dTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE=
0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjk5OTU1OH0/498bf936766c481aabb3fc22a3554ab9feeead=
a8c84c3585f5ef58fc0950a8c3" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;fon=
t-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">whole column</a></u> about this called <i>The =
Biden-ing of Donald Trump</i>, and what happened on the debate stage on Tue=
sday night was the Biden-ing of Trump by a <i>factor of 10. </i><br/><br/>N=
ot only was he <i>punished</i> by the split screen with Harris, but he evin=
ced all of Biden=E2=80=99s flaws with no greater degree of messaging discip=
line or focus or clarity. It=E2=80=99s notable that he didn=E2=80=99t achie=
ve <i>any </i>of the directives he was supposed to achieve. He took the bai=
t incessantly, and instead of talking about immigration he decided to talk =
about Harris=E2=80=99s crowd size, and that she was going to usher in World=
 War III, and then he launched into the riff about dogs and pets being cons=
umed by Haitian immigrants. In many ways, this is <i>exactly </i>what Biden=
 did in June, when he was given an abortion question that was in his wheelh=
ouse and he got lost in the middle
of the answer, and ended up talking about immigration=E2=80=94a topic he, i=
n fact, did <i>not </i>want to be talking about. <br/><br/>One of my longti=
me hobbyhorses is the decline of Trump=E2=80=99s mental acuity. It=E2=80=99=
s not that the guy hasn=E2=80=99t pulled it together=E2=80=94he=E2=80=99s <=
i>unable </i>to pull it together. He=E2=80=99s not rattled, undisciplined, =
or distracted=E2=80=94he=E2=80=99s dotty, demented, mentally diminished. Th=
at became undeniably clear on Tuesday night, when, on the biggest stage wit=
h the biggest stakes, Trump failed to move the ball forward a <i>single </i=
>inch on any of his political goals or strategic objectives. Among his staf=
f, advisers, allies, and friends, the debate brought home his unraveling wi=
th a vengeance. <br/></td>
         </tr>
